<li id="cite_note-72"><b><a href="#cite_ref-72" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFClarke1984">Clarke, Arthur C. (1984). <i>Profiles of the Future: An Inquiry Into the Limits of the Possible</i>. New York, New York: Holt, Rinehart &amp; Wilson. pp.&#160;205n. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/0030697832" class="internal">ISBN 0030697832</a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Profiles+of+the+Future%3A+An+Inquiry+Into+the+Limits+of+the+Possible&amp;rft.aulast=Clarke&amp;rft.aufirst=Arthur+C.&amp;rft.au=Clarke%2C+Arthur+C.&amp;rft.date=1984&amp;rft.pages=pp.%26nbsp%3B205n&amp;rft.place=New+York%2C+New+York&amp;rft.pub=Holt%2C+Rinehart+%26+Wilson&amp;rft.isbn=0030697832&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Arthur_C._Clarke"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span> "INTELSAT, the International Telecommunications Satellite Organisation which operates the global system, has started calling it the Clarke orbit. Flattered though I am, honesty compels me to point out that the concept of such an orbit predates my 1945 paper 'Extra Terrestrial Relays' by at least twenty years. I didn't invent it, but only annexed it."</li>
